Integration test verifying plain-profile rendering against the real `dict.steno` corpus checked into the repo root; a Rust port of `test/render.test.ts`, so behavior must track that TS test file if it changes.

It reads `../../dict.steno` relative to `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR` (i.e., repo-root `dict.steno`), parses it via `parse_source`, and expands it via `expand_dict(&entries, None)`; any change to the corpus file or to those two functions' output shape can break these assertions since they hardcode specific strokes (`STKWR-PBGS/TPH-FLT`, `STKWR-PBGS/PH-FLT`, `STKWR-BGS`) and their exact expected rendered output. `typed()` and `by_stroke()` return `Option`/silently `.unwrap()` in tests, so a missing stroke or parse failure surfaces as a panic, not a descriptive assertion failure.

Key invariants asserted: terminal entries render with `{^}...{#Up End Left*N}{^}` movement back to a marker position, escaping braces as `\{`/`\}`; non-terminal entries strip all bracing (no `{#` movement) and drop auto-paired delimiters (`()[]<>`); single-line terminal entries omit the `{#Up}` component since no vertical movement is needed. `full_plain_dict` asserts `build_plain_dict` on the full corpus produces zero collisions and yields >1000 dictionary keys — a coarse regression check on overall corpus health, not on any single entry.